British Airways Plc's &lt;BAB.L> Maypassenger and cargo traffic figures provided evidence ofrecovery from last year's setbacks and this trend will bereflected in first quarter results due in August, chairman LordKing told the annual meeting.    Earlier this month, the newly-privatised airline reported a29 pct rise in passenger traffic figures for May, with cargotraffic up 22 pct.    In the year to March, British Airways reported a drop inpre-tax profits to 162 mln stg from 195 mln previously.However, King said this result was satisfactory, consideringthe difficulties posed by the Chernobyl disaster and the U.S.Raid on Libya.    He said British Airways intended to return its tour traveloperations to profitability, when questioned by shareholders.    In 1986/87, this division reported an operating loss ofnine mln stg, the fifth year of losses. However, he said thegroup might reconsider its course of action if a turnaroundseemed unlikely in the long-term. Reuter&#3;